{"title": "Caxtons: A Family Picture", "description": "The quiet country life of the Caxton family is interrupted by a visit to London. There the son, Pisistratus, is offered the position of secretary to a leader in Parliament. That parliamentarian's wife was loved as a girl by both Pisistratus' father and uncle; but she had passed them both by to make a marriage better suited to an ambitious woman. By a freak of fate, Pisistratus now falls in love with her daughter Fannie. <br><br>\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, Pisistratus' uncle is estranged from his own son. Between each person's pride, the rift doesn't seem possible to settle. Pisistratus does what he can to heal the wounds and reunite the family.<br><br>\r\n\r\nA further outline of this story would give no idea of its charm. The mutual affection of the Caxtons is finely indicated, and the gradations of light and shade make a beautiful picture. Never before had Bulwer written with so light a touch and so gentle a humor, and this novel has been called the most brilliant and attractive of productions. His gentle satire of certain phrases of political life was founded, doubtless, on actual experience. - Summary modified from \"Warner's Synopsis of Books Ancient and Modern, Vol. 2\" (1910)", "duration": 82401, "language": "English", "authors": [{"id": "868", "name": "Edward Bulwer-Lytton"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/caxtons_2108_librivox/caxtons_2108.jpg", "copyright_year": "1849", "genres": ["Published 1800 -1900"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "LibriVox Volunteers"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "TriciaG"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "TriciaG"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "TriciaG"}], "sections": [{"section": 0, "title": "Preface", "readers": [14199], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/caxtons_2108_librivox/caxtons_00_bulwer-lytton_64kb.mp3", "duration": 220}, {"section": 1, "title": "Part 1, Chapter 1", "readers": [14199], "path": "https://www.archive.org/downlo